For the greatest dry white wines of the world, one must look to Burgundy. We particularly salute the great 66s—wines of fantastic breed, airy lightness, and extraordinary bouquet. A few of the 1967s, par- ticularly in Chablis, have proven excellent but they are hard to come by. The ’64s are fruity and full- bodied and similar to the ’59s.
